    "body": "I was eventually able to get some peers recently by asking in the #ethereum IRC channel and being given a admin.addPeer('enode://...') command. It took a while after that, but eventually I was connected to 10-15 peers. It seems that the bootstrap code wasn't finding any non-full peers for me.\n\nHow is the \"--maxpeers\" thing meant to work? Suppose there are 100 peers, each with --maxpeers=25. Each will eventually connect to 25% of the nodes, leaving all 100 nodes \"full\" and unavailable for new peers to connect to. Bitcoin has the concept of \"incoming\" and \"outgoing\" connections. Each peer will only attempt to make a certain number (8 by default) of outgoing connections, leaving the rest of its 'maxpeers' allocation available for other peers to connect to. Is there any similar scheme in ethereum that attempts to ensure it's always possible for new nodes to find non-full peers?\n",
