    "body": "Sorry to comment on such an old issue, but I don't see any other mention of the \"node removal strategy\".  I was just wondering if that ever happened.  We're running a private chain and this is an issue.  Here's a 1hr sample of the errors (where background.log is the geth output with verbosity=6), during which no peers were successfully added: \r\n\r\n```\r\n$ grep failed background.log | sed 's/.*://g' | sed 's/- .*//g' | sort | uniq -c | sort -r -n\r\n  15485  use of closed network connection\r\n   2654  not found\r\n   1940  Too many peers\r\n    979  Genesis block mismatch\r\n    650  EOF\r\n    249  Useless peer\r\n     37  i/o timeout\r\n     37  An existing connection was forcibly closed by the remote host.\r\n     18  expected handshake, got 6\r\n      9  shutting down\r\n      2  NetworkId mismatch\r\n```\r\n\r\nI believe \"not found\" is when the node was not found in the local DB, so that's actually a count of new peers that were attempted.  You can see the large majority of new peers have too many peers, and many of the others are just not from our network.  Not sure why there are so many \"use of closed network connection\".",
